'''Javier Aguirre Onaindía''' ({{IPA|es|xaˈβjeɾ aˈɣire}}; born 1 December 1958), nicknamed ''El Vasco'' (The Basque), is a Mexican football [[Manager (association football)|manager]] and former [[Association football|footballer.]] He is currently manager of the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]].

As a player, he is best remembered for his time at [[Club América]], where he made his debut and won a [[Liga MX|Primera División]] championship, and later at [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]], where he amassed over 100 appearances before retiring. On the international stage, he earned 59 caps and scored 14 goals for Mexico, including representing his country at the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=23 July 2024 |title=Quien es Javier Aguirre, el nuevo director técnico de la Selección Mexicana para el Mundial 2026 |url=https://www.infobae.com/mexico/deportes/2024/07/23/quien-es-javier-aguirre-el-nuevo-director-tecnico-de-la-seleccion-mexicana-para-el-mundial-2026/ |access-date=6 April 2026 |website=infobae |language=es-MX}}</ref>

Upon retiring, Aguirre transitioned into management and quickly established a reputation as a tactically flexible and resilient coach. After leading [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]] to prominence, he took charge of the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]], guiding them to the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] — a feat he would repeat at the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]] and [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026]] editions as well.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Del mediocampo al banquillo, el recorrido mundialista de Javier Aguirre |url=https://www.fifa.com/es/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/javier-aguirre-historia-en-mundiales |access-date=6 April 2026 |website=www.fifa.com}}</ref>

His managerial career extended well beyond Mexico. At [[Atlético Madrid]], he delivered consistent top-table finishes in [[La Liga]] and secured regular European qualification; he also guided both [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]] and [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] to [[Copa del Rey]] finals. On the international stage, he coached the national teams of [[Japan national football team|Japan]] and [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]], achieving mixed success.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 July 2020 |title=Javier Aguirre: Su carrera como entrenador |url=https://www.informador.mx/deportes/Javier-Aguirre-Su-carrera-como-entrenador-20201207-0037.html |access-date=6 April 2026 |website=El Informador |language=es-MX}}</ref>

==Early life==
Aguirre was born in [[Mexico City]] on 1 December 1958. He earned the nickname ''El Vasco'' due to his parents’ [[Basques|Basque heritage]]. His mother hailed from [[Guernica]] and his father from [[Ispaster]]; the couple migrated to Mexico in 1950. Through them, Aguirre qualified for a Spanish passport, a valuable asset that eased his professional career abroad. Reflecting his roots, he gave his three sons traditional Basque names: Iker, Ander, and Iñaki.<ref>{{cite news |title=¿Por qué le dicen Vasco a Javier Aguirre?|trans-title=Why do they call Javier Aguirre Basque? |url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/liga-mx/por-que-le-dicen-vasco-a-javier-aguirre |access-date=12 April 2024 |work=Medio Tiempo |date=2 November 2021 |language=Spanish}}</ref>

==Playing career==

===Club===
Aguirre began his professional career with [[Club América]], making his first-team debut in 1979 before moving to the [[Los Angeles Aztecs]] the following year. After a brief stint in the United States, he returned to his former club, where he quickly cemented his place as a regular starter. His second spell with Club América proved highly successful, culminating in the [[1983–84 Mexican Primera División season|1983–84]] championship title, in which he scored in the decisive final.

Aguirre then joined [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]], spending two seasons with the club before heading to Spain to sign with [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]]. His time in [[La Liga]] was disrupted by a serious injury that sidelined him for several months, and after just a year abroad, he returned to Mexico to play for [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]]. There, he made over 100 appearances before bringing his playing career to a close.

===International===
Aguirre earned 59 international caps for the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]] between 1983 and 1992, scoring 13 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/miscellaneous/mex-recintlp.html |title=Mexico record international footballers |work=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |access-date=30 December 2011 |archive-date=30 July 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730073426/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/mex-recintlp.html  }}</ref>
He was a member of the squad at the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]], held in Mexico, where he appeared in the quarter-final against [[Germany national football team|West Germany]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manuel Negrete señala los errores que eliminaron a la selección mexicana del Mundial de México 86 |trans-title=Manuel Negrete points out the errors that eliminated the Mexico national team from the Mexico 86 World Cup|url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/futbol/seleccion-mx/2020/06/17/5eea3c1f268e3ebb4d8b45f1.html |access-date=8 February 2023 |work=Marca |date=17 June 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref> During the game, Aguirre was sent off, becoming the first Mexican player to be dismissed in a World Cup fixture.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Almaguer |first1=Rubén |title=Javier Aguirre, el primer mexicano expulsado en Mundiales|trans-title=Javier Aguirre, the first Mexican to be sent off in a World Cup |url=https://www.posta.com.mx/deportes/futbol-mx/javier-aguirre-el-primer-mexicano-expulsado-en-mundiales/17889 |access-date=8 February 2023 |work=Posta |date=21 June 2021 |language=Spanish}}</ref>

==Managerial career==

===Early years===
After his retirement, Aguirre took up managing, first at [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]] and then [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]], where he won his first title as manager, the [[Primera División de México Invierno 1999|Invierno 1999]] championship.

=== First spell with Mexico ===
On 22 June 2001, Aguirre was appointed manager of the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]], replacing [[Enrique Meza]]. The team sat fifth in their qualifying group for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] following a 3–1 away defeat to [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]], part of a dismal run of just one win in 12 matches.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goff |first1=Steven |title=Mexican Coach Meza Resigns |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/2001/06/22/mexican-coach-meza-resigns/cb41589f-989b-4557-82e3-d7e785d8391a/ |access-date=7 February 2020 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=22 June 2001}}</ref>
In his debut match on 1 July, ''El Tri'' defeated the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] at home. Mexico ultimately qualified in second place behind [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] after securing a crucial 3–0 victory over Honduras at the [[Estadio Azteca]] on 11 November.<ref>{{cite news |title=Borgetti keeps Mexican hopes alive|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2002/1417592.stm |access-date=7 February 2020 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2 July 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Juegos del Recuerdo: México 3-0 Honduras Y ¡Nos fuimos al Mundial!|trans-title=Games from Memory: Mexico 3–0 Honduras And we're going to the World Cup! |url=https://www.goal.com/es-mx/news/4854/concacaf/2013/03/12/3819550/juegos-del-recuerdo-m%C3%A9xico-3-0-honduras-y-nos-fuimos-al |access-date=7 February 2020 |publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]] |date=12 March 2013}}</ref>

In July 2001, Aguirre led Mexico at the [[2001 Copa América|Copa América]] in Colombia, where they defeated [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Chile national football team|Chile]] and [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] before narrowly losing the final 1–0 to the hosts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lea |first1=Greg |title=The 2001 Copa América: A tournament of classic upsets that may never have taken place |url=https://thesefootballtimes.co/2018/12/06/the-copa-america-of-2001-was-an-eventful-tournament-like-few-in-history/ |access-date=7 February 2020 |publisher=These Football Times |date=6 December 2018}}</ref> A year later at the 2002 World Cup in South Korea and Japan, his side topped their group at Italy's expense before falling 2–0 to the United States in the Round of 16.<ref>{{cite news |title=USA see off sorry Mexico |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/matches_wallchart/mexico_v_usa/default.stm |access-date=7 February 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 June 2002}}</ref>

===Osasuna===
On 6 June 2002, while leading Mexico at the World Cup, Aguirre joined [[La Liga]] club [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]] after previous manager [[Miguel Ángel Lotina]] quit for [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta de Vigo]]; he had previously played for the [[Navarre]]se club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aguirre signs Osasuna deal |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/team_pages/mexico/newsid_2030000/2030198.stm |access-date=7 February 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2002}}</ref> In his first season in [[Pamplona]], the club reached the semi-finals of the [[Copa del Rey]], losing 4–2 on aggregate to [[Recreativo de Huelva]].<ref>{{cite news |title=El Recreativo revivirá ante Osasuna el histórico cruce de semifinales de 2003|trans-title=Recreativo will revive against Osasuna the historical semi-final duel of 2003 |url=https://www.huelvainformacion.es/recreativo/Recreativo-Copa-Rey-Osasuna_0_1428157506.html |access-date=7 February 2020 |publisher=Huelva Información |date=14 January 2020 |language=es}}</ref>

In [[2004–05 Copa del Rey|2004–05]], Aguirre went one better, guiding Osasuna to the [[2005 Copa del Rey Final|cup final]], where they lost 2–1 after extra time to [[Real Betis]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dani delivers for Betis |url=https://pt.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=309157.html |access-date=7 February 2020 |publisher=[[UEFA]] |date=12 June 2005}}{{dead link|date=March 2025|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In the [[2005–06 La Liga|following league season]], the ''Rojillos'' beat [[Sevilla FC]] to a joint-best 4th place and their first qualification to the [[UEFA Champions League]], having led the table after 11 games.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |title=Party time in Pamplona and celebrations down in Seville |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/may/17/europeanfootball.sport1 |access-date=7 February 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 May 2006}}</ref>

===Atlético Madrid===
[[File:Javier Aguirre in Moscow.jpg|thumb|upright|Aguirre as Atlético Madrid manager in 2007]]
On 24 May 2006, days after Osasuna finished the season in fourth, Aguirre signed a one-year contract to replace [[Pepe Murcia]] at [[Atlético Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Atlético confirm Aguirre appointment |url=https://www.uefa.com/news-media/news/01b5-0f848983574b-a05af3e1647f-1000--atletico-confirm-aguirre-appointment/ |access-date=7 February 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=24 May 2006}}</ref> After a fourth-place finish in 2008 confirmed a place in the Champions League, he extended his deal by another year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aguirre committed to Atlético project |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=698149.html |access-date=7 February 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=20 May 2008}}{{dead link|date=March 2025|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

Aguirre was dismissed from the [[Vicente Calderón Stadium]] on 2 February 2009, after a run of two points from five games. He was replaced by the team's former goalkeeper [[Abel Resino]], who arrived from [[CD Castellón]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Aguirre makes way for Resino at Atletico |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/02/03/spain.atletico/ |access-date=7 February 2020 |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=3 February 2009}}</ref>

===Second spell with Mexico===
On 3 April 2009, Aguirre was officially appointed as the new manager of the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]], replacing [[Sven-Göran Eriksson]]. He was officially presented in a press conference two weeks later. At the press conference, he stated: "I am not a savior. My aim is that we regain our identity and convince people that we can achieve this together". His annual salary was reported to be US$1,635,000.<ref>{{cite web|title="Vasco", la Azul te espera |url=http://especiales.laprensagrafica.com/2009/hexagonal/?p=916 |newspaper=[[La Prensa Grafica]] |trans-title="Vasco", the blue awaits you |language=es |date=16 April 2009 |access-date=30 March 2010 |archive-date=13 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713183850/http://especiales.laprensagrafica.com/2009/hexagonal/?p=916 |url-status=live  }}</ref>

On 6 June 2009, Aguirre debuted in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification|2010 FIFA World Cup qualifier]] against [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]], losing 2–1. However, he rebounded four days later with a 2–1 win over [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]].

On 9 July 2009, Aguirre was ejected in an incident during the [[2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] match versus [[Panama national football team|Panama]]. During a play along the sideline, Aguirre kicked Panamanian player [[Ricardo Phillips (footballer, born 1975)|Ricardo Phillips]], triggering Phillips to push Aguirre, causing ejections for both Aguirre and Phillips and delaying the match for over 10 minutes due to the refusal of the player from Panama to leave the field.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ivan |last=Orozco |title=Perez gives Panama 1–1 draw with Mexico |url=http://www.goldcup.org/page/GoldCup/NewsDetail/0,,12802~1718433,00.html |work=[[CONCACAF]] |date=10 July 2009 |access-date=10 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220191649/http://www.goldcup.org/page/GoldCup/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C12802~1718433%2C00.html |archive-date=20 February 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>  Aguirre apologized to the Mexican fans, media, football players and staff, but never extended such courtesy to Philips or the Panamanian team. He was suspended for three games and the [[Federación Mexicana de Fútbol Asociación|Mexican Football Federation]] was fined US$25,000 by [[CONCACAF]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico coach Javier Aguirre suspended after brawl in Panama match |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/jul/12/mexico-javier-aguirre-panama |date=12 June 2009 |access-date=30 March 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529155409/http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/jul/12/mexico-javier-aguirre-panama |archive-date=29 May 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref>

On 26 July 2009, Aguirre led Mexico to its fifth [[2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]] title and its first win against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] outside of Mexico since 1999.<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael |last=Lewis |title=U.S. kicking self after 5–0 blowout loss to Mexico in CONCACAF Gold Cup |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more_sports/2009/07/27/2009-07-27_us_mexico.html |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |date=26 July 2009 |access-date=27 July 2009 |archive-date=31 August 2009 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831035854/http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more_sports/2009/07/27/2009-07-27_us_mexico.html  }}</ref> He then led Mexico to a comeback win over the same opposition at the [[Estadio Azteca]] on 12 August 2009 and followed it up by winning 3–0 in [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], putting Mexico closer to a qualifying spot for the World Cup that seemed to be an impossible task at the time when Eriksson was sacked. On 10 October 2009, Mexico beat El Salvador in the Estadio Azteca 4–1, qualifying Mexico for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].

After that, in their last hexagonal game against [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]], they tied 2–2, ending the World Cup qualifying journey.

On 30 June 2010, Aguirre resigned as coach of Mexico following their failure to reach the quarter-finals of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] in South Africa. Mexico finished second in [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group A|Group A]], ahead of hosts [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] and [[France national football team|France]], but their progress was halted in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup knockout stage|round of 16]] where they were defeated 3–1 by [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/story/_/id/804496/ce/uk/?cc=5739&ver=global |title=Aguirre quits Mexico job |date=30 June 2010 |work=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]] |publisher=[[ESPN]] |access-date=30 June 2010 |archive-date=21 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021185903/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/story/_/id/804496/ce/uk/?cc=5739&ver=global  }}</ref>

Aguirre's decision-making during the qualifying stages and during the World Cup garnered criticism, with journalist [[José Ramón Fernández (journalist)|José Ramón Fernández]] calling him the worst coach at the World Cup after France's [[Raymond Domenech]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.educacioncontracorriente.org/portal/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4533%3Ael-universal&catid=16%3Anoticias&Itemid=29 |title="El peor técnico del Mundial después de Raymond Domenech es Javier Aguirre": José Ramón Fernández |access-date=19 September 2018 |archive-date=18 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218131320/http://www.educacioncontracorriente.org/portal/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4533%3Ael-universal&catid=16%3Anoticias&Itemid=29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His insistence on playing team-less striker [[Guillermo Franco]], while keeping [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] striker [[Javier Hernández]] on the bench bewildered many fans and commentators.<ref>{{cite web|date=23 June 2010 |url=http://www.espndeportes.com/blogs/index?name=georgina_gonzalez_ontiveros&month=6&year=2010 |title=Pequeña teoría sobre Guille y compañía |trans-title=Small theory Guille and Co. |author=Georgina González Ontiveros |work=ESPN |archive-date=9 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809024758/http://www.espndeportes.com/blogs/index?name=georgina_gonzalez_ontiveros&month=6&year=2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Aguirre came under additional criticism for his refusal to explain his decisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/articulo/javier-aguirre-es-un-necio-y-terco-carlos-albert |title=Javier Aguirre es un necio y terco: Carlos Albert |trans-title=Javier Aguirre is stupid and stubborn: Carlos Albert |date=22 June 2010 |access-date=5 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325074900/http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/articulo/javier-aguirre-es-un-necio-y-terco-carlos-albert |archive-date=25 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>

During the run up to the World Cup Aguirre expressed his desire to coach in the Premier League in England, but did not receive any offers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.eluniversal.com.mx/weblogs_detalle11393.html |title=La sordera de nuestro Führer |author=Guillermo Fadanelli |newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]] |date=21 June 2010 |access-date=5 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304144906/http://blogs.eluniversal.com.mx/weblogs_detalle11393.html |archive-date=4 March 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref>

===Real Zaragoza===
On 17 November 2010, Aguirre became the manager of [[Real Zaragoza]].<ref>{{cite web|language=es |url=http://www.realzaragoza.com/noticias/14336 |title=Javier Aguirre presentado |trans-title=Javier Aguirre presented |work=realzaragoza.com |date=18 November 2010 |archive-date=1 March 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301161327/http://www.realzaragoza.com/noticias/14336}}</ref> On 29 December 2011, he was relieved of his duties following the club's descent into the relegation spots.<ref>{{cite news|language=es|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2011/12/29/203233873-el-real-zaragoza-rescinde-contrato-con-javier-aguirre|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120910173726/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2011/12/29/203233873-el-real-zaragoza-rescinde-contrato-con-javier-aguirre|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 September 2012|title=El Real Zaragoza rescinde contrato con Javier Aguirre|trans-title=Real Zaragoza terminate contract with Javier Aguirre|work=[[La Jornada]]|date=29 December 2011|access-date=30 December 2011}}</ref>

===Espanyol===
[[File:Wiki javier aguirre.jpg|thumb|upright|Aguirre managing Espanyol in December 2013]]
On 28 November 2012, Aguirre was appointed manager of [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]], who were 20th in the [[La Liga]] table at the time. On 16 May 2014, Aguirre announced his departure. He was succeeded by [[Sergio González Soriano|Sergio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/114/mexico/2014/05/16/4822499/former-el-tri-coach-aguirre-leaves-espanyol |title=Former Mexico manager Javier Aguirre is set to leave his post in La Liga |last=Marshall |first=Tom |work=Goal.com |date=16 May 2014 |access-date=19 June 2014 |archive-date=20 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720211121/http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/114/mexico/2014/05/16/4822499/former-el-tri-coach-aguirre-leaves-espanyol |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Espanyol: Sergio Gonzalez is named new coach |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27598069 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |access-date=28 May 2014 |date=27 May 2014 |archive-date=28 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140528140429/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27598069 |url-status=live  }}</ref>

===Japan===
In August 2014, Aguirre became the new manager of the [[Japan national football team|Japan national team]], replacing [[Alberto Zaccheroni]], who had resigned following the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]].<ref name="japantimes">{{cite news | url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2014/08/11/soccer/international-soccer/aguirre-embraces-massive-challenge-japans-new-soccer-boss/#.VH_TBF3xOmA | title=Aguirre embraces 'massive challenge' as Japan's new soccer boss | work=The Japan Times | date=11 August 2014 | access-date=4 December 2014 | author=Fielding, Gus}}</ref> At the [[2015 AFC Asian Cup]], Japan won all three of its group matches, scoring seven goals and conceding none, though was knocked out in the quarter-final by the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]].

On 3 February 2015, the [[Japan Football Association]] announced the termination of Aguirre's contract. This decision followed the confirmation that Spanish anti-corruption investigators had indicted Aguirre for alleged involvement in an ongoing match-fixing investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/japanrealtime/2015/02/03/japan-fires-soccer-coach-javier-aguirre/?guid=BL-JRTB-19114&dsk=y |title=Japan fires soccer coach Javier Aguirre |last=Hongo |first=Jun |date=3 February 2015 |access-date=3 February 2015 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref>

===Al Wahda===
On 18 June 2015, Aguirre was hired as new manager of the [[Al-Wahda F.C.|Al-Wahda FC]] from [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/2015/06/18/futbol/futbol_internacional/1434631046.html|title=Javier Aguirre ficha por el Al Wahda|author=Cerezo, Hugo|work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|date=18 June 2015|language=es}}</ref> On 21 May 2017, after leading Al Wahda to the President's Cup championship victory, Aguirre decided to step down as manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenationalnews.com/sport/i-ll-be-a-wahdawi-forever-out-going-al-wahda-manager-javier-aguirre-says-farewell-1.24612/|title='I'll be a Wahdawi forever': Out-going Al Wahda manager Javier Aguirre says farewell|access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref>

===Egypt===
In July 2018, Aguirre was on a four-man shortlist for the vacant [[Egypt national football team|Egyptian national team]] manager job.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44951260|title=Egypt announces four-man coaching shortlist to replace Cuper|date=25 July 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=19 September 2018}}</ref> He was appointed manager in August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45037965|title=Egypt appoint Mexican Javier Aguirre as their new manager|work=BBC|date=1 August 2018}}</ref> During the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]], which was hosted in Egypt, the national team was eliminated by [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] in the Round of 16. As a result, Aguirre was sacked along with the whole technical and administrative staff of the national team for the disappointing result.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/35849/11758221/egypt-sack-javier-aguirre-after-defeat-to-south-africa-in-africa-cup-of-nations-last-16|title=Egypt sack Javier Aguirre after defeat to South Africa in Africa Cup of Nations last 16|date=7 July 2019|publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48899049|title=Africa Cup of Nations: Egypt sack head coach Javier Aguirre after last-16 exit|date=7 July 2019|website=BBC Sport|access-date=27 August 2019}}</ref>

===Leganés===
In November 2019, Aguirre returned to La Liga, taking over [[CD Leganés|Leganés]] after the dismissal of [[Mauricio Pellegrino]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kostapoulos |first1=Panos |title=Leganes set to appoint Javier Aguirre as their new head coach |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2019/11/04/5dbf5f27268e3ef0538b4572.html |access-date=7 February 2020 |work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |date=4 November 2019}}</ref> In July 2020, he stepped down from his position after the club was relegated on the final day of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jan/24/real-madrid-copa-del-rey-leganes-defeat|work=The Guardian|date=24 January 2018|access-date=25 January 2018|title=Real Madrid dumped out of Copa del Rey by Leganés at Bernabéu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrasco |first1=Javi |title=Javier Aguirre no seguirá en el Leganés|trans-title=Javier Aguirre will not continue at Leganés |url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/futbol/mexicanos-mundo/2020/07/20/5f15b69922601d531d8b4618.html |access-date=27 July 2020 |work=Marca |date=20 July 2020 |language=es}}</ref>

===Monterrey===
Although Aguirre had previously stated that his coaching days in Mexican football were behind him, he took the reins of [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]] in December 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marshall |first1=Tom |title=Javier Aguirre returns to Liga MX as Monterrey head coach |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/soccer-transfers/story/4256168/javier-aguirre-returns-to-liga-mx-as-monterrey-head-coach |access-date=27 December 2021 |publisher=ESPN FC|date=7 December 2020}}</ref> On 28 October 2021, Aguirre led Monterrey to the [[2021 CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF Champions League]] title with a 1–0 triumph over [[Club América|América]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fmfstateofmind.com/2021/10/29/22751957/2021-concacaf-champions-league-final-match-recap-rayados-de-monterrey-1-club-america-0 | title=Monterrey win 2021 CONCACAF Champions League title | date=29 October 2021 }}</ref>

On 26 February 2022, he was dismissed from his position after a run of disappointing results.<ref>{{cite web|first=Adriana|last=Garcia|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/monterrey/story/4605641/monterrey-fires-javier-aguirre-after-fan-dramaliga-mx-struggles|title=Monterrey fires Javier Aguirre after fan drama, Liga MX struggles|publisher=ESPN|date=26 February 2022}}</ref>

===Mallorca===
On 24 March 2022, Aguirre returned to La Liga. He joined [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]], who were one point above the relegation zone with nine games remaining.<ref>{{cite news |title=Struggling Spanish club Mallorca hires Mexican coach Aguirre |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/2022/03/24/struggling-spanish-club-mallorca-hires-mexican-coach-aguirre.html |access-date=8 February 2023 |work=Toronto Star |agency=Associated Press |date=24 March 2022}}</ref> Mallorca avoided relegation on the last day of the season.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |title='Walking dead' of Cádiz and Mallorca rise up to send Granada into abyss |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2022/may/23/walking-dead-cadiz-mallorca-granada-la-liga-relegation |access-date=8 February 2023 |work=The Guardian |date=23 May 2022}}</ref>

Aguirre led Mallorca to the [[2024 Copa del Rey final|Copa del Rey]] final. They lost to [[Athletic Bilbao]] on penalties after a 1–1 draw at the [[Estadio de La Cartuja]] in [[Seville]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Mallorca pay the penalty in Seville |url=https://www.majorcadailybulletin.com/sport/real-mallorca/2024/04/07/122823/mallorca-pay-the-penalty.html |access-date=12 April 2024 |work=Mallorca Daily Bulletin |date=7 April 2024}}</ref> On 22 May 2024, Aguirre and Mallorca parted ways.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rcdmallorca.es/noticias/javier-aguirre-no-continuara-en-el-rcd-mallorca-la-proxima-temporada|title=Javier Aguirre no continuará en el RCD Mallorca la próxima temporada|publisher=Real Club Deportivo Mallorca|language=es|date=22 May 2024}}</ref>

===Third spell with Mexico===
On 22 July 2024, the [[Mexican Football Federation]] announced Aguirre as the new manager of the [[Mexico national football team|national team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/40619552/mexico-javier-aguirre-head-coach-rafa-marquez-assistant|title=Mexico names Javier Aguirre head coach, Rafa Marquez assistant|publisher=ESPN|date=22 July 2024}}</ref>

In November 2024, Aguirre was hit by a beer can, leaving him bloodied after his team’s 2–0 loss to Honduras in the Nations League quarter-final. Despite the injury, Aguirre downplayed the incident, focusing on congratulating the victors. The Mexican Football Federation condemned the attack, urging CONCACAF to act, while CONCACAF promised an investigation. Honduras manager [[Reinaldo Rueda]] also expressed disappointment over the violence.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kearns |first=Sean |title=Mexico coach Aguirre hit with beer can after Honduras defeat |date=16 November 2024 |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cdrd203451do |website=BBC News |access-date=16 November 2024}}</ref> The incident was also condemned by FIFA President [[Gianni Infantino]], calling it "horrible" and called for an investigation of the incident.<ref>{{cite web|date=17 November 2024|title=Gianni Infantino lamenta agresión que sufrió Javier Aguirre|url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/nota/_/id/14455033/gianni-infantino-javier-aguirre-agresion-honduras-vs-mexico|access-date=17 November 2024|publisher=ESPN Deportes}}</ref>

In March 2025, Aguirre helped Mexico achieve its first [[2024–25 CONCACAF Nations League|Nations League]] title after defeating [[Panama national football team|Panama]] 2–1 in the [[2025 CONCACAF Nations League final|final]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/44383231/mexico-turn-back-clock-first-concacaf-nations-league-title|title=Mexico's old-school approach takes them to first Concacaf Nations League title|date=24 March 2025|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> In July that year, Aguirre won his second [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]] after defeating rivals the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] 2–1 in the [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup final|final]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/45684192/mexico-beats-usmnt-win-10th-gold-cup|title=Mexico takes down USMNT to win 10th Gold Cup|date=7 July 2025|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>

